---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { hosts, show } from '../data/podcast';
import { u } from '../lib/url';
---

<Base title="About" description={show.description}>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="wrap prose-wrap">
      <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
      <h1 class="title">Thinking With… is a pedagogical experiment</h1>
      <p class="lede">{show.ethos}</p>

      <div class="body">
        <h2>How it started</h2>
        <p>
          We started Thinking With… in 2020, during the depths of the pandemic. We were all
          stuck, largely isolated, and intellectually starving — teaching online, our usual
          conferences canceled, with little of the ordinary opportunity to think and talk with
          other people. Then, on some random day in June, John called Nathaniel and said,
          “hey, you should read this really smart dissertation proposal I just got from a
          student of mine, Nate DeProspo.” Things spiraled from there. Nathaniel and Nate met,
          along with John, on this new thing called “Zoom,” to talk about Nate's project — and
          to ask him why in the world he was so invested in G. W. F. Hegel of all people.
        </p>
        <p>
          We kept Zooming, as a reading group. After a while we imagined our discussions were
          for an audience. It was something of a joke at first — us, starting a podcast on
          esoteric philosophy. But it got us thinking about how we'd relate to listeners. If we
          were to make a podcast, what would the goal be, especially since we spend most of our
          time teaching in a classroom? There's no shortage of material on the internet aimed at
          teaching. And one of the ideas we kept circling back to is that the most powerful
          teaching and learning we do has little to do with presenting and remembering
          propositions, arguments, and histories. For us, philosophy <em>and</em> rhetoric are
          about teaching styles of thinking — and we learn styles of thinking by getting swept
          up in a current.
        </p>
        <p>
          We wanted our podcast to be a stream to get caught up in, for our listeners and for
          us. We wanted to “think with.” The question was, think with <em>what?</em> The answer
          had to be ambiguous and precise at once: think with each other, with texts, with
          intellectual traditions and longstanding but ever-mutating questions and concepts. We
          wanted to imagine that our listeners weren't taking notes for an exam but were swept up
          and thinking along with us — and imagining that audience shaped how we read, spoke, and
          positioned ourselves while recording. That's why we added the ellipsis: the whole idea
          was an experiment in thinking with… an ever-changing complex of things.
        </p>

        <h2>Why Hegel, and what came after</h2>
        <p>
          We recorded our first “season” on Hegel's <em>Phenomenology of Spirit</em>. If the goal
          had been a big audience, this may have been the single worst text we could have chosen:
          early-19th-century, infamously dense, and — despite Hegel's enormous influence — the
          subject of a critical mass of critiques across the 20th century. Who reads Hegel
          anymore? What rhetorical theorist reads Hegel? Almost no one. Except Nate DeProspo, who
          thought Hegel shows us something about the nature of subjectivity that most contemporary
          theories would rather wish away. So we read the <em>Phenomenology</em> to better
          understand Hegel, to better understand Nate's affinity for him, and to launch the maiden
          voyage of the show.
        </p>
        <p>
          The season was a pedagogical experiment. We read the book slowly. Very slowly — a few
          pages per episode. We read passages closely, tried to understand them, and thought with
          them. We published twelve episodes and covered the preface: a whole forty-five pages. We
          liked it so much we did it again — with Gilles Deleuze's <em>The Logic of Sense</em>;
          and again with Martin Heidegger's <em>What Is Called Thinking?</em>; and again with a
          set of essays and chapters by Jacques Derrida; and again with Friedrich Nietzsche's
          <em>The Gay Science</em>; and again with Heidegger's <em>Being and Time</em>.
        </p>

        <h2>What's changing</h2>
        <p>
          After six years, we want to change things up a little. The main goal is the same: this is
          still a pedagogical experiment in provoking styles of thinking by thinking with… But
          we're organizing things a bit differently. First, there's this website — with archives of
          our seasons, this page so you can actually know who we are, and ways to contact us and
          subscribe.
        </p>
        <p>
          We're also reorganizing our upcoming season. We're making a concerted effort to briefly
          overview the focus of each episode to orient listeners before we dive in. And we're
          organizing the season around an idea — <strong>“Critique”</strong> — rather than a single
          text. Alongside the episodes, we'll post our thoughts and responses to the texts we read,
          to engage and provoke our listeners on the questions we're working through, and we'll
          publish something of a “syllabus” for our schedule of readings so you can keep track of
          where we are and where we're going. We're also planning to co-write a more robust essay,
          likely for an academic journal, and to dedicate a few episodes to a real-time glimpse of
          what it's like to write and publish an academic article.
        </p>
        <p>
          So stay tuned. Things are going to be different. But also the same. Is there any other
          option?
        </p>

        <h2>Who we are</h2>
        <p>We're three academics who specialize in rhetorical theory.</p>
        <ul class="hosts">
          {hosts.map((h) => (
            <li class="host">
              <a class="host-link" href={u(`/about/${h.slug}`)}>
                <span class="host-name">{h.name}</span>
                <span class="host-role muted">{h.role}</span>
                <span class="host-more">Read more →</span>
              </a>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="cta card">
        <p>New here? Start with any season — the point was never to begin at the beginning.</p>
        <div class="cta-actions">
          <a href={u('/podcasts')} class="btn btn--primary">Browse the seasons</a>
          <a href={u('/contact#subscribe')} class="btn btn--ghost">Join the email list</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .title { font-size: clamp(2.2rem, 6vw, 3.4rem); }
  .lede { margin-bottom: 2.4rem; }
  .body h2 { font-size: 1.7rem; margin-top: 2.4rem; }
  .body p { font-size: 1.12rem; }
  .body em { font-style: italic; }
  .hosts { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 1.2rem 0 0; display: grid; gap: 1rem; }
  .host {
    background: var(--paper-card);
    border: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
  }
  .host-link {
    display: grid; gap: 0.15rem;
    padding: 1.1rem 1.3rem;
    text-decoration: none; color: inherit;
    transition: background 0.15s ease;
    border-radius: var(--radius);
  }
  .host-link:hover { background: var(--paper-2); }
  .host-name { font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.25rem; }
  .host-role { font-size: 0.95rem; }
  .host-more { font-family: var(--font-body); font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--accent-deep); margin-top: 0.3rem; }
  .cta { margin-top: 3rem; padding: 1.8rem 2rem; text-align: center; }
  .cta p { font-size: 1.15rem; margin-bottom: 1.2rem; }
  .cta-actions { display: flex; gap: 0.8rem; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap; }
</style>
